Your question:

Is it true that for every request browser automatically sends refresh token?

Short answer:

👉 Not for every request. Only for requests that match cookie rules.

Let’s break this properly.

🧠 When Does Browser Send a Cookie?

Browser automatically sends a cookie only if:

The request URL matches the cookie’s domain

The request path matches the cookie’s path

It satisfies SameSite rules

It’s HTTPS if Secure is set

🟢 Example Setup

Server sets cookie:

Set-Cookie: refresh_token=xyz;
HttpOnly;
Secure;
SameSite=Strict;
Path=/refresh;
Domain=api.example.com

Now browser stores it.

🔎 Will It Be Sent With Every Request?
✅ It WILL be sent when:

Request matches:

https://api.example.com/refresh

Because:

Domain matches

Path matches

HTTPS

SameSite rules satisfied

❌ It will NOT be sent when:

Request is:

https://api.example.com/courses

Because cookie Path is /refresh

So Path matters.

🟢 If Path is "/"

If server sets:

Path=/

Then cookie is sent to all endpoints under that domain.

Example:

/courses
/profile
/orders
/anything

So yes — in that case, it is sent with every request to that domain.

🔐 Now Let’s Talk SameSite=Strict

If SameSite=Strict:

Browser will NOT send cookie if request originates from another site.

Example:

User is on:

evil.com

And evil.com tries to call:

https://api.example.com/refresh

Browser will NOT send the cookie.

So CSRF protection kicks in.

🎯 Real-World Best Practice

Usually refresh token cookie is configured like:

HttpOnly
Secure
SameSite=Strict
Path=/refresh

So it is sent ONLY to /refresh endpoint.

Not to every API call.

That limits exposure.

🧠 So Final Answer

If interviewer asks:

Does browser send refresh token with every request?

You say:

The browser automatically sends the refresh token cookie only when the request matches the cookie's domain, path, and security rules. If the cookie Path is set to /, it will be sent with all requests to that domain. However, in secure implementations, the Path is often restricted to /refresh so it is only sent when renewing tokens.

That’s a strong answer.

